TY  - JOUR
T1  - Money Illusion and Balance-of-Payments Adjustment
AU  - Murphy, J. C.
AU  - Das, S. K.
Y1  - 1976/02/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260410
DO  - 10.1086/260410
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 73
EP  - 82
VL  - 84
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Money illusion, taking the form of lagged price perceptions and viewed in a competitive general equilibrium context, is shown in this paper to reduce the change in a country's balance of payments attributable to a devaluation of given size. Illusion's effect on adjustment is also shown to be probably greater under flexible than under fixed exchange-rate arrangements. The results contrast with a view that illusion, in disguising real-income changes, facilitates the elimination of a balance-of-payments deficit.
AB  - Money illusion, taking the form of lagged price perceptions and viewed in a competitive general equilibrium context, is shown in this paper to reduce the change in a country's balance of payments attributable to a devaluation of given size. Illusion's effect on adjustment is also shown to be probably greater under flexible than under fixed exchange-rate arrangements. The results contrast with a view that illusion, in disguising real-income changes, facilitates the elimination of a balance-of-payments deficit.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260410
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260410
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Economic Value of Statute Reform: The Case of Liberalized Abortion
AU  - Deyak, Timothy A.
AU  - Smith, V. Kerry
Y1  - 1976/02/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260411
DO  - 10.1086/260411
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 83
EP  - 99
VL  - 84
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper develops a model for estimating the costs associated with the institutional and legal restrictions related to the states' abortion statutes. A travel-cost demand model is estimated with data for legal abortions obtained in New York State. The purpose is to determine the value--for women seeking abortions--of the 1973 Supreme Court ruling which liberalized abortion codes. The estimated benefits foregone in the absence of liberalization, over a 10-year period with a 10 percent discount rate, range from 12 million to 30 million in present value. It is important to note that this study makes no attempt to measure the losses to certain groups in society as a result of the liberalization.
AB  - This paper develops a model for estimating the costs associated with the institutional and legal restrictions related to the states' abortion statutes. A travel-cost demand model is estimated with data for legal abortions obtained in New York State. The purpose is to determine the value--for women seeking abortions--of the 1973 Supreme Court ruling which liberalized abortion codes. The estimated benefits foregone in the absence of liberalization, over a 10-year period with a 10 percent discount rate, range from 12 million to 30 million in present value. It is important to note that this study makes no attempt to measure the losses to certain groups in society as a result of the liberalization.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260411
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260411
Y2  - 2024/03/22
